<p><b>Wikipedia</b> (<span class="nowrap"><span class="noexcerpt"><a href="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/01/GT_Wikipedia_BE.ogg" title="Listen"><img alt="Listen" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3b/Speakerlink-new.svg/11px-Speakerlink-new.svg.png" width="11" height="11" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3b/Speakerlink-new.svg/17px-Speakerlink-new.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3b/Speakerlink-new.svg/22px-Speakerlink-new.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="11" data-file-height="11" /></a><sup><span class="IPA" style="color:#00e;font:bold 80% sans-serif;padding:0 .1em"><a href="/wiki/File:GT_Wikipedia_BE.ogg" title="File:GT Wikipedia BE.ogg">i</a></span></sup></span><span class="IPA nopopups noexcerpt"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English" title="Help:IPA for English">/<span style="border-bottom:1px dotted"><span title="// secondary stress follows"></span><span title="'w' in 'wind'">w</span><span title="// short 'i' in 'bid'"></span><span title="'k' in 'kind'">k</span><span title="// or // 'e' in 'roses'"></span><span title="// primary stress follows"></span><span title="'p' in 'pie'">p</span><span title="/i/ long 'e' in 'seed'">i</span><span title="'d' in 'dye'">d</span><span title="/i/ 'y' in 'happy'">i</span><span title="// 'a' in 'about'"></span></span>/</a></span></span> or <span class="nowrap"><span class="noexcerpt"><a href="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4c/GT_Wikipedia_AE.ogg" title="Listen"><img alt="Listen" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3b/Speakerlink-new.svg/11px-Speakerlink-new.svg.png" width="11" height="11" //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3b/Speakerlink-new.svg/22px-Speakerlink-new.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="11" data-file-height="11" /></a><sup><span class="IPA" style="color:#00e;font:bold 80% sans-serif;padding:0 .1em"><a href="/wiki/File:GT_Wikipedia_AE.ogg" title="File:GT Wikipedia AE.ogg">i</a></span></sup></span><span class="IPA nopopups noexcerpt"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA_for_English" title="Help:IPA for English">/<span style="border-bottom:1px dotted"><span title="// secondary stress follows"></span><span title="'w' in 'wind'">w</span><span title="// short 'i' in 'bid'"></span><span title="'k' in 'kind'">k</span><span title="/i/ 'y' in 'happy'">i</span><span title="// primary stress follows"></span><span title="'p' in 'pie'">p</span><span title="/i/ long 'e' in 'seed'">i</span><span title="'d' in 'dye'">d</span><span title="/i/ 'y' in 'happy'">i</span><span title="// 'a' in 'about'"></span></span>/</a></span></span> <a href="/wiki/Help:Pronunciation_respelling_key" title="Help:Pronunciation respelling key"><small title="English pronunciation respelling"><i><b>WIK</b>-i-<b>PEE</b>-dee-</i></small></a>) is a free <a href="/wiki/Online_encyclopedia" title="Online encyclopedia">online encyclopedia</a> with the aim to allow anyone to edit articles.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">[3]</a></sup> Wikipedia is the largest and most popular general <a href="/wiki/Reference_work" title="Reference work">reference work</a> on the Internet<sup id="cite_ref-Tancer_7-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Tancer-7">[4]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Woodson_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Woodson-8">[5]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">[6]</a></sup> and is ranked among the ten most popular websites.<sup id="cite_ref-Alexa_siteinfo_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Alexa_siteinfo-10">[7]</a></sup> Wikipedia is owned by the nonprofit <a href="/wiki/Wikimedia_Foundation" title="Wikimedia Foundation">Wikimedia Foundation</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">[8]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">[9]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">[10]</a></sup></p>
<p>Wikipedia was launched on January 15, 2001, by <a href="/wiki/Jimmy_Wales" title="Jimmy Wales">Jimmy Wales</a> and <a href="/wiki/Larry_Sanger" title="Larry Sanger">Larry Sanger</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-KockJungSyn2016_14-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-KockJungSyn2016-14">[11]</a></sup> Sanger coined <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Wikipedia" class="extiw" title="wikt:Wikipedia">its name</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-MiliardWho_15-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-MiliardWho-15">[12]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-J_Sidener_16-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-J_Sidener-16">[13]</a></sup> a <a href="/wiki/Portmanteau" title="Portmanteau">portmanteau</a> of <i><a href="/wiki/Wiki" title="Wiki">wiki</a></i><sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">[notes 4]</a></sup> and encyclo<i>pedia</i>. There was only the English language version initially, but it quickly developed similar versions in other languages, which differ in content and in editing practices. With <a href="/wiki/Special:Statistics" title="Special:Statistics">5,430,154 articles</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">[notes 5]</a></sup> the <a href="/wiki/English_Wikipedia" title="English Wikipedia">English Wikipedia</a> is the largest of the more than 290 Wikipedia encyclopedias. Overall, Wikipedia consists of more than 40 million articles in more than 250 different languages<sup id="cite_ref-CBS_20-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CBS-20">[15]</a></sup> and, as of February 2014<sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Wikipedia&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, it had 18 billion page views and nearly 500 million unique visitors each month.<sup id="cite_ref-small_screen_21-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-small_screen-21">[16]</a></sup></p>
<p>As of March 2017, Wikipedia has about forty thousand high-quality articles known as <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Featured_Article" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:Featured Article">Featured Articles</a> and <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Good_Article" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:Good Article">Good Articles</a> that cover vital topics.<sup id="cite_ref-FMonday_feat_article_patterns_2_22-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FMonday_feat_article_patterns_2-22">[17]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-IBM_feat_articles_hidden_pattern_2_23-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-IBM_feat_articles_hidden_pattern_2-23">[18]</a></sup> In 2005, <i><a href="/wiki/Nature_(journal)" title="Nature (journal)">Nature</a></i> published a peer review comparing 42 science articles from <i><a href="/wiki/Encyclop%C3%A6dia_Britannica" title="Encyclopædia Britannica">Encyclopædia Britannica</a></i> and Wikipedia, and found that Wikipedia's level of accuracy approached <i>Encyclopædia Britannica</i><span class="nowrap" style="padding-left:0.1em;">'</span>s.<sup id="cite_ref-GilesJ2005Internet_24-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-GilesJ2005Internet-24">[19]</a></sup></p>
<p>Wikipedia <a href="/wiki/Criticism_of_Wikipedia" title="Criticism of Wikipedia">has been criticized</a> for allegedly <a href="/wiki/Bias_in_Wikipedia" class="mw-redirect" title="Bias in Wikipedia">exhibiting systemic bias</a>, presenting a mixture of "truths, half truths, and some falsehoods",<sup id="cite_ref-EdwinBlack_25-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-EdwinBlack-25">[20]</a></sup> and, in controversial topics, being subject to manipulation and <a href="/wiki/Spin_(public_relations)" class="mw-redirect" title="Spin (public relations)">spin</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Petrilli_26-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Petrilli-26">[21]</a></sup></p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span></h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/History_of_Wikipedia" title="History of Wikipedia">History of Wikipedia</a></div>
<div class="thumb tmulti tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:223px;max-width:223px">
<div class="tsingle" style="float:left;margin:1px;width:102px;max-width:102px">
<div class="thumbimage"><a href="/wiki/File:Jimmy_Wales_September_2015.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Jimmy_Wales_September_2015.jpg/100px-Jimmy_Wales_September_2015.jpg" width="100" height="142" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Jimmy_Wales_September_2015.jpg/150px-Jimmy_Wales_September_2015.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Jimmy_Wales_September_2015.jpg/200px-Jimmy_Wales_September_2015.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2088" data-file-height="2962" /></a></div>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Nupedia">Nupedia</span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Nupedia_logo_and_wordmark.png" class="image"><img alt="Logo reading &quot;Nupedia.com the free encyclopedia&quot; in blue with large initial &quot;N&quot;" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a4/Nupedia_logo_and_wordmark.png/220px-Nupedia_logo_and_wordmark.png" width="220" height="51" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a4/Nupedia_logo_and_wordmark.png/330px-Nupedia_logo_and_wordmark.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a4/Nupedia_logo_and_wordmark.png/440px-Nupedia_logo_and_wordmark.png 2x" data-file-width="500" data-file-height="117" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Nupedia_logo_and_wordmark.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Wikipedia originally developed from another encyclopedia project called <a href="/wiki/Nupedia" title="Nupedia">Nupedia</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Other collaborative online encyclopedias were attempted before Wikipedia, but none were successful.<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27">[22]</a></sup></p>
<p>Wikipedia began as a complementary project for <a href="/wiki/Nupedia" title="Nupedia">Nupedia</a>, a free online <a href="/wiki/English_language" title="English language">English-language</a> encyclopedia project whose articles were written by experts and reviewed under a formal process.<sup id="cite_ref-KockJungSyn2016_14-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-KockJungSyn2016-14">[11]</a></sup> Nupedia was founded on March 9, 2000, under the ownership of <a href="/wiki/Bomis" title="Bomis">Bomis</a>, a <a href="/wiki/Web_portal" title="Web portal">web portal</a> company. Its main figures were <a href="/wiki/Jimmy_Wales" title="Jimmy Wales">Jimmy Wales</a>, the <abbr title="chief executive officer">CEO</abbr> of Bomis, and <a href="/wiki/Larry_Sanger" title="Larry Sanger">Larry Sanger</a>, <a href="/wiki/Editing" title="Editing">editor-in-chief</a> for Nupedia and later Wikipedia. Nupedia was licensed initially under its own Nupedia <a href="/wiki/Open_Content" class="mw-redirect" title="Open Content">Open Content</a> License, switching to the <a href="/wiki/GNU_Free_Documentation_License" title="GNU Free Documentation License">GNU Free Documentation License</a> before Wikipedia's founding at the urging of <a href="/wiki/Richard_Stallman" title="Richard Stallman">Richard Stallman</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-stallman1999_28-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-stallman1999-28">[23]</a></sup> Sanger and Wales founded Wikipedia.<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated1_29-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated1-29">[24]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Meyers_30-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Meyers-30">[25]</a></sup> While Wales is credited with defining the goal of making a publicly editable encyclopedia,<sup id="cite_ref-SangerMemoir_31-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SangerMemoir-31">[26]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Sanger_32-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Sanger-32">[27]</a></sup> Sanger is credited with the strategy of using a <a href="/wiki/Wiki" title="Wiki">wiki</a> to reach that goal.<sup id="cite_ref-WM_foundation_of_WP_1_33-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WM_foundation_of_WP_1-33">[28]</a></sup> On January 10, 2001, Sanger proposed on the Nupedia <a href="/wiki/Electronic_mailing_list" title="Electronic mailing list">mailing list</a> to create a wiki as a "feeder" project for Nupedia.<sup id="cite_ref-nupedia_feeder_from_WP_1_34-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nupedia_feeder_from_WP_1-34">[29]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;">
<div id="mwe_player_0" class="PopUpMediaTransform" style="width:220px;" videopayload="&lt;div class=&quot;mediaContainer&quot; style=&quot;width:854px&quot;&gt;&lt;video id=&quot;mwe_player_1&quot; poster=&quot;//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/ff/How_Wikipedia_contributes_to_free_knowledge.webm/854px--How_Wikipedia_contributes_to_free_knowledge.webm.jpg&quot; <h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Launch_and_early_growth">Launch and early growth</span></h3>
<p>Wikipedia was launched on January 15, 2001, as a single English-language edition at www.wikipedia.com,<sup id="cite_ref-WikipediaHome_35-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WikipediaHome-35">[30]</a></sup> and announced by Sanger on the Nupedia mailing list.<sup id="cite_ref-SangerMemoir_31-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SangerMemoir-31">[26]</a></sup> Wikipedia's policy of "neutral point-of-view"<sup id="cite_ref-NPOV_36-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NPOV-36">[31]</a></sup> was codified in its first months. Otherwise, there were relatively few rules initially and Wikipedia operated independently of Nupedia.<sup id="cite_ref-SangerMemoir_31-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SangerMemoir-31">[26]</a></sup> Originally, Bomis intended to make Wikipedia a business for profit.<sup id="cite_ref-Seth-Finkelstein_37-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Seth-Finkelstein-37">[32]</a></sup></p>
<p>Wikipedia gained early contributors from Nupedia, <a href="/wiki/Slashdot" title="Slashdot">Slashdot</a> postings, and <a href="/wiki/Web_search_engine" title="Web search engine">web search engine</a> indexing. By August 8, 2001, Wikipedia had over 8,000 articles.<sup id="cite_ref-Wikipedia_August_08.2C_2001_38-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Wikipedia_August_08.2C_2001-38">[33]</a></sup> On September 25, 2001, Wikipedia had over 13,000 articles.<sup id="cite_ref-Wikipedia_September_25.2C_2001_39-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Wikipedia_September_25.2C_2001-39">[34]</a></sup> By the end of 2001, it had grown to approximately 20,000 articles and 18 language editions. It had reached 26 language editions by late 2002, 46 by the end of 2003, and 161 by the final days of 2004.<sup id="cite_ref-WP_early_language_stats_1_40-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WP_early_language_stats_1-40">[35]</a></sup> Nupedia and Wikipedia coexisted until the former's servers were taken down permanently in 2003, and its text was incorporated into Wikipedia. The <a href="/wiki/English_Wikipedia" title="English Wikipedia">English Wikipedia</a> passed the mark of two million articles on September 9, 2007, making it the largest encyclopedia ever assembled, surpassing even the 1408 <i><a href="/wiki/Yongle_Encyclopedia" title="Yongle Encyclopedia">Yongle Encyclopedia</a></i>, which had held the record for almost 600 years.<sup id="cite_ref-EB_encyclopedia_41-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-EB_encyclopedia-41">[36]</a></sup></p>
<p>Citing fears of commercial advertising and lack of control in Wikipedia, users of the <a href="/wiki/Spanish_Wikipedia" title="Spanish Wikipedia">Spanish Wikipedia</a> <a href="/wiki/Fork_(software_development)" title="Fork (software development)">forked</a> from Wikipedia to create the <i><a href="/wiki/Enciclopedia_Libre_Universal_en_Espa%C3%B1ol" title="Enciclopedia Libre Universal en Español">Enciclopedia Libre</a></i> in February 2002.<sup id="cite_ref-EL_fears_and_start_1_42-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-EL_fears_and_start_1-42">[37]</a></sup> These moves encouraged Wales to announce that Wikipedia would not display advertisements, and to change Wikipedia's domain from <i>wikipedia.com</i> to <i>wikipedia.org</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-Shirky_43-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Shirky-43">[38]</a></sup></p>
<p>Though the English Wikipedia reached three million articles in August 2009, the growth of the edition, in terms of the numbers of articles and of contributors, appears to have peaked around early 2007.<sup id="cite_ref-guardian_WP_user_peak_1_44-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-guardian_WP_user_peak_1-44">[39]</a></sup> Around 1,800 articles were added daily to the encyclopedia in 2006; by 2013 that average was roughly 800.<sup id="cite_ref-WP_growth_modelling_1_45-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WP_growth_modelling_1-45">[40]</a></sup> A team at the <a href="/wiki/Palo_Alto_Research_Center" class="mw-redirect" title="Palo Alto Research Center">Palo Alto Research Center</a> attributed this slowing of growth to the project's increasing exclusivity and resistance to change.<sup id="cite_ref-wikisym_slowing_growth_1_46-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-wikisym_slowing_growth_1-46">[41]</a></sup> Others suggest that the growth is flattening naturally because articles that could be called "<a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/low-hanging_fruit" class="extiw" title="wikt:low-hanging fruit">low-hanging fruit</a>"—topics that clearly merit an article—have already been created and built up extensively.<sup id="cite_ref-bostonreview_the_end_of_WP_1_47-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bostonreview_the_end_of_WP_1-47">[42]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48">[43]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-stanford_WP_lack_of_future_growth_1_49-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-stanford_WP_lack_of_future_growth_1-49">[44]</a></sup></p>
<p><span id="Decline_in_participation_since_2009"></span> In November 2009, a researcher at the <a href="/wiki/Rey_Juan_Carlos_University" class="mw-redirect" title="Rey Juan Carlos University">Rey Juan Carlos University</a> in <a href="/wiki/Madrid" title="Madrid">Madrid</a> (<a href="/wiki/Spain" title="Spain">Spain</a>) found that the English Wikipedia had lost 49,000 editors during the first three months of 2009; in comparison, the project lost only 4,900 editors during the same period in 2008.<sup id="cite_ref-guardian_editors_leaving_1_50-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-guardian_editors_leaving_1-50">[45]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-51">[46]</a></sup> <i>The Wall Street Journal</i> cited the array of rules applied to editing and disputes related to such content among the reasons for this trend.<sup id="cite_ref-WSJ_WP_losing_editors_1_52-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WSJ_WP_losing_editors_1-52">[47]</a></sup> Wales disputed these claims in 2009, denying the decline and questioning the methodology of the study.<sup id="cite_ref-telegraph_Wales_WP_not_losing_editors_1_53-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-telegraph_Wales_WP_not_losing_editors_1-53">[48]</a></sup> Two years later, in 2011, Wales acknowledged the presence of a slight decline, noting a decrease from "a little more than 36,000 writers" in June 2010 to 35,800 in June 2011. In the same interview, Wales also claimed the number of editors was "stable and sustainable".<sup id="cite_ref-wiki-women_54-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-wiki-women-54">[49]</a></sup> A 2013 article titled "The Decline of Wikipedia" in MIT's <i><a href="/wiki/Technology_Review" class="mw-redirect" title="Technology Review">Technology Review</a></i> questioned this claim. The article revealed that since 2007, Wikipedia had lost a third of the volunteer editors who update and correct the online encyclopedia and those still there have focused increasingly on minutiae.<sup id="cite_ref-Simonite-2013_55-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Simonite-2013-55">[50]</a></sup> In July 2012, <i><a href="/wiki/The_Atlantic" title="The Atlantic">the Atlantic</a></i> reported that the number of administrators is also in decline.<sup id="cite_ref-56" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-56">[51]</a></sup> In the November 25, 2013, issue of <i><a href="/wiki/New_York_(magazine)" title="New York (magazine)">New York</a></i> magazine, Katherine Ward stated "Wikipedia, the sixth-most-used website, is facing an internal crisis".<sup id="cite_ref-57" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-57">[52]</a></sup> <span id="BlackoutProtest"></span></p>

<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Milestones">Milestones</span></h3>
<p>In January 2007, Wikipedia entered for the first time the top-ten <a href="/wiki/List_of_most_popular_websites" title="List of most popular websites">list of the most popular websites</a> in the U.S., according to <a href="/wiki/ComScore" title="ComScore">comScore</a> Networks. With 42.9 million unique visitors, Wikipedia was ranked number 9, surpassing the <i><a href="/wiki/New_York_Times" class="mw-redirect" title="New York Times">New York Times</a></i> (#10) and <a href="/wiki/Apple_Inc." title="Apple Inc.">Apple</a> (#11). This marked a significant increase over January 2006, when the rank was number 33, with Wikipedia receiving around 18.3 million unique visitors.<sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-58">[53]</a></sup> As of March 2015<sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Wikipedia&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, Wikipedia has rank 5<sup id="cite_ref-Alexa_siteinfo_10-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Alexa_siteinfo-10">[7]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Alexa_top_59-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Alexa_top-59">[54]</a></sup> among websites in terms of popularity according to <a href="/wiki/Alexa_Internet" title="Alexa Internet">Alexa Internet</a>. In 2014, it received 8 billion pageviews every month.<sup id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-60">[55]</a></sup> On February 9, 2014, <i>The New York Times</i> reported that Wikipedia has 18 billion <a href="/wiki/Page_view" title="Page view">page views</a> and nearly 500 million <a href="/wiki/Unique_visitor" class="mw-redirect" title="Unique visitor">unique visitors</a> a month, "according to the ratings firm comScore."<sup id="cite_ref-small_screen_21-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-small_screen-21">[16]</a></sup></p>
<p>On January 18, 2012, the English Wikipedia participated in a series of coordinated protests against two proposed laws in the United States Congress—the <a href="/wiki/Stop_Online_Piracy_Act" title="Stop Online Piracy Act">Stop Online Piracy Act</a> (SOPA) and the <a href="/wiki/PROTECT_IP_Act" title="PROTECT IP Act">PROTECT IP Act</a> (PIPA)—by <a href="/wiki/2012_Wikipedia_blackout" class="mw-redirect" title="2012 Wikipedia blackout">blacking out its pages for 24 hours</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-LA_Times_Jan_19_61-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-LA_Times_Jan_19-61">[56]</a></sup> More than 162 million people viewed the blackout explanation page that temporarily replaced Wikipedia content.<sup id="cite_ref-BBC_WP_blackout_protest_1_62-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-BBC_WP_blackout_protest_1-62">[57]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-63" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-63">[58]</a></sup></p>
<p>Loveland and Reagle argue that, in process, Wikipedia follows a long tradition of historical encyclopedias that accumulated improvements piecemeal through "<a href="/wiki/Stigmergy" title="Stigmergy">stigmergic</a> accumulation".<sup id="cite_ref-sagepub_WP_and_encyclopedic_production_1_64-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sagepub_WP_and_encyclopedic_production_1-64">[59]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-theatlantic_WP_actually_a_reversion_1_65-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-theatlantic_WP_actually_a_reversion_1-65">[60]</a></sup></p>
<p>On January 20, 2014, Subodh Varma reporting for <i>The Economic Times</i> indicated that not only had Wikipedia's growth flattened but that it has "lost nearly 10 per cent of its page-views last year. That's a decline of about 2 billion between December 2012 and December 2013. Its most popular versions are leading the slide: page-views of the English Wikipedia declined by 12 per cent, those of German version slid by 17 per cent and the Japanese version lost 9 per cent."<sup id="cite_ref-economictimes.indiatimes.com_66-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-economictimes.indiatimes.com-66">[61]</a></sup> Varma added that, "While Wikipedia's managers think that this could be due to errors in counting, other experts feel that Google's <a href="/wiki/Knowledge_Graph" title="Knowledge Graph">Knowledge Graphs</a> project launched last year may be gobbling up Wikipedia users."<sup id="cite_ref-economictimes.indiatimes.com_66-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-economictimes.indiatimes.com-66">[61]</a></sup> When contacted on this matter, Clay Shirky, associate professor at New York University and fellow at Harvard's Berkman Center for Internet and Security indicated that he suspected much of the page view decline was due to Knowledge Graphs, stating, "If you can get your question answered from the search page, you don't need to click [any further]."<sup id="cite_ref-economictimes.indiatimes.com_66-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-economictimes.indiatimes.com-66">[61]</a></sup></p>
<p>By the end of December 2016, Wikipedia was ranked fifth in the most popular websites globally.<sup id="cite_ref-Alexa_67-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Alexa-67">[62]</a></sup></p>

<p><br /></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Openness">Openness</span></h2>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:History_Comparison_Example_(Vector).png" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/History_Comparison_Example_%28Vector%29.png/220px-History_Comparison_Example_%28Vector%29.png" width="220" height="138" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/History_Comparison_Example_%28Vector%29.png/330px-History_Comparison_Example_%28Vector%29.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/History_Comparison_Example_%28Vector%29.png/440px-History_Comparison_Example_%28Vector%29.png 2x" data-file-width="1225" data-file-height="768" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:History_Comparison_Example_(Vector).png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Differences between versions of an article are highlighted as shown</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Unlike traditional encyclopedias, Wikipedia follows the <a href="/wiki/Procrastination" title="Procrastination">procrastination</a> principle<sup id="cite_ref-69" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-69">[notes 6]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-zittrain_70-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-zittrain-70">[64]</a></sup> regarding the security of its content.<sup id="cite_ref-zittrain_70-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-zittrain-70">[64]</a></sup> It started almost entirely open—anyone could create articles, and any Wikipedia article could be edited by any reader, even those who did not have a Wikipedia account. Modifications to all articles would be published immediately. As a result, any article could contain inaccuracies such as errors, ideological biases, and nonsensical or irrelevant text.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Restrictions">Restrictions</span></h3>
<p>Due to the increasing popularity of Wikipedia, popular editions, including the English version, have introduced editing restrictions in some cases. For instance, on the English Wikipedia and some other language editions, only registered users may create a new article.<sup id="cite_ref-71" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-71">[65]</a></sup> On the English Wikipedia, among others, some particularly controversial, sensitive and/or vandalism-prone pages have been protected to some degree.<sup id="cite_ref-WP_protection_policy_1_72-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WP_protection_policy_1-72">[66]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-73" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-73">[67]</a></sup> A frequently vandalized article can be <i><a href="/wiki/Help:Semi-protection" class="mw-redirect" title="Help:Semi-protection">semi-protected</a></i> or <i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:ECP" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:ECP">extended confirmed protected</a></i>, meaning that only <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Autoconfirmed" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:Autoconfirmed">autoconfirmed</a> or <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:XCON" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:XCON">extended confirmed</a> editors are able to modify it.<sup id="cite_ref-74" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-74">[68]</a></sup> A particularly contentious article may be locked so that only <a href="/wiki/Administrators_(Wikipedia)" class="mw-redirect" title="Administrators (Wikipedia)">administrators</a> are able to make changes.<sup id="cite_ref-75" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-75">[69]</a></sup></p>
<p>In certain cases, all editors are allowed to submit modifications, but review is required for some editors, depending on certain conditions. For example, the <a href="/wiki/German_Wikipedia" title="German Wikipedia">German Wikipedia</a> maintains "stable versions" of articles,<sup id="cite_ref-WP_some_sites_stable_versions_1_76-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WP_some_sites_stable_versions_1-76">[70]</a></sup> which have passed certain reviews. Following protracted trials and community discussion, the English Wikipedia introduced the "pending changes" system in December 2012.<sup id="cite_ref-BInsider_pending_changes_intro_1_77-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-BInsider_pending_changes_intro_1-77">[71]</a></sup> Under this system, new and unregistered users' edits to certain controversial or vandalism-prone articles are reviewed by established users before they are published.<sup id="cite_ref-78" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-78">[72]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Wikipedia_editing_interface.png" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/Wikipedia_editing_interface.png/220px-Wikipedia_editing_interface.png" width="220" height="105" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/Wikipedia_editing_interface.png/330px-Wikipedia_editing_interface.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/Wikipedia_editing_interface.png/440px-Wikipedia_editing_interface.png 2x" data-file-width="1912" data-file-height="909" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Wikipedia_editing_interface.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
The editing interface of Wikipedia</div>
</div>
</div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Review_of_changes">Review of changes</span></h3>
<p>Although changes are not systematically reviewed, the software that powers Wikipedia provides certain tools allowing anyone to review changes made by others. The "History" page of each article links to each revision.<sup id="cite_ref-79" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-79">[notes 7]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Torsten_Kleinz_80-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Torsten_Kleinz-80">[73]</a></sup> On most articles, anyone can undo others' changes by clicking a link on the article's history page. Anyone can view the <a href="/wiki/Help:Recent_changes" title="Help:Recent changes">latest changes</a> to articles, and anyone may maintain a <a href="/wiki/Recent_changes" class="mw-redirect" title="Recent changes">"watchlist"</a> of articles that interest them so they can be notified of any changes. "New pages patrol" is a process whereby newly created articles are checked for obvious problems.<sup id="cite_ref-81" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-81">[74]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 2003, economics PhD student Andrea Ciffolilli argued that the low <a href="/wiki/Transaction_cost" title="Transaction cost">transaction costs</a> of participating in a <a href="/wiki/Wiki" title="Wiki">wiki</a> create a catalyst for collaborative development, and that features such as allowing easy access to past versions of a page favor "creative construction" over "creative destruction".<sup id="cite_ref-FMonday_collaborative_effort_1_82-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FMonday_collaborative_effort_1-82">[75]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Vandalism">Vandalism</span></h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Vandalism_on_Wikipedia" title="Vandalism on Wikipedia">Vandalism on Wikipedia</a></div>
<p>Any change or edit that manipulates content in a way that purposefully compromises the integrity of Wikipedia is considered vandalism. The most common and obvious types of vandalism include additions of obscenities and crude humor. Vandalism can also include advertising and other types of spam.<sup id="cite_ref-upenn_link_spamming_1_83-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-upenn_link_spamming_1-83">[76]</a></sup> Sometimes editors commit vandalism by removing content or entirely blanking a given page. Less common types of vandalism, such as the deliberate addition of plausible but false information to an article, can be more difficult to detect. Vandals can introduce irrelevant formatting, modify page semantics such as the page's title or categorization, manipulate the underlying code of an article, or use images disruptively.<sup id="cite_ref-WP_vandalism_manipulation_1_84-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WP_vandalism_manipulation_1-84">[77]</a></sup></p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:John_Seigenthaler_Sr._speaking.jpg" class="image"><img alt="White-haired elderly gentleman in suit and tie speaks at a podium." src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2f/John_Seigenthaler_Sr._speaking.jpg/220px-John_Seigenthaler_Sr._speaking.jpg" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2f/John_Seigenthaler_Sr._speaking.jpg/330px-John_Seigenthaler_Sr._speaking.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2f/John_Seigenthaler_Sr._speaking.jpg/440px-John_Seigenthaler_Sr._speaking.jpg 2x" data-file-width="800" data-file-height="600" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:John_Seigenthaler_Sr._speaking.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
American journalist <a href="/wiki/John_Seigenthaler" title="John Seigenthaler">John Seigenthaler</a> (1927–2014), subject of the <a href="/wiki/Seigenthaler_incident" class="mw-redirect" title="Seigenthaler incident">Seigenthaler incident</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Obvious vandalism is generally easy to remove from Wikipedia articles; the median time to detect and fix vandalism is a few minutes.<sup id="cite_ref-MIT_IBM_study_85-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-MIT_IBM_study-85">[78]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-CreatingDestroyingAndRestoringValue_86-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CreatingDestroyingAndRestoringValue-86">[79]</a></sup> However, some vandalism takes much longer to repair.<sup id="cite_ref-Seigenthaler_87-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Seigenthaler-87">[80]</a></sup></p>
<p>In the <a href="/wiki/Seigenthaler_biography_incident" class="mw-redirect" title="Seigenthaler biography incident">Seigenthaler biography incident</a>, an anonymous editor introduced false information into the biography of American political figure <a href="/wiki/John_Seigenthaler" title="John Seigenthaler">John Seigenthaler</a> in May 2005. Seigenthaler was falsely presented as a suspect in the assassination of John F. Kennedy.<sup id="cite_ref-Seigenthaler_87-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Seigenthaler-87">[80]</a></sup> The article remained uncorrected for four months.<sup id="cite_ref-Seigenthaler_87-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Seigenthaler-87">[80]</a></sup> Seigenthaler, the founding editorial director of <i><a href="/wiki/USA_Today" title="USA Today">USA Today</a></i> and founder of the <a href="/wiki/Freedom_Forum" title="Freedom Forum">Freedom Forum</a> <a href="/wiki/First_Amendment_Center" title="First Amendment Center">First Amendment Center</a> at <a href="/wiki/Vanderbilt_University" title="Vanderbilt University">Vanderbilt University</a>, called Wikipedia co-founder Jimmy Wales and asked whether he had any way of knowing who contributed the misinformation. Wales replied that he did not, although the perpetrator was eventually traced.<sup id="cite_ref-book_The_World_is_Flat_1_88-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-book_The_World_is_Flat_1-88">[81]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-89" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-89">[82]</a></sup> After the incident, Seigenthaler described Wikipedia as "a flawed and irresponsible research tool".<sup id="cite_ref-Seigenthaler_87-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Seigenthaler-87">[80]</a></sup> This incident led to policy changes at Wikipedia, specifically targeted at tightening up the verifiability of <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Biographies_of_living_persons" title="Wikipedia:Biographies of living persons">biographical articles of living people</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-90" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-90">[83]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Policies_and_laws"><span id="Rules_and_laws_governing_content">Policies and laws</span><span id="Rules_and_laws_governing_content_and_editor_behavior"></span></span></h2>
<p><span id="Censorship"></span></p>
<table class="infobox" style="width:22em;width: 220px; float: right; clear: right; margin:0 0 1.0em 1.0em">
<caption>External video</caption>
<tbody><tr>
<td colspan="2" style="text-align:center"><a href="/wiki/File:Jimbo_at_Fosdem_cropped.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Jimbo at Fosdem cropped.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/47/Jimbo_at_Fosdem_cropped.jpg/210px-Jimbo_at_Fosdem_cropped.jpg" width="210" height="244" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/47/Jimbo_at_Fosdem_cropped.jpg/315px-Jimbo_at_Fosdem_cropped.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/47/Jimbo_at_Fosdem_cropped.jpg/420px-Jimbo_at_Fosdem_cropped.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1536" data-file-height="1786" /></a></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan="2" style="text-align:center;text-align: left"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Nuvola_apps_kaboodle.svg/16px-Nuvola_apps_kaboodle.svg.png" width="16" height="16" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Nuvola_apps_kaboodle.svg/24px-Nuvola_apps_kaboodle.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Nuvola_apps_kaboodle.svg/32px-Nuvola_apps_kaboodle.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="128" data-file-height="128" /> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.cbsnews.com/news/wikipedia-jimmy-wales-morley-safer-60-minutes/">Wikimania</a>, <i><a href="/wiki/60_Minutes" title="60 Minutes">60 Minutes</a></i>, <a href="/wiki/CBS" title="CBS">CBS</a>, 20 minutes, April 5, 2015, co-founder Jimmy Wales at Fosdem</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
<p>Content in Wikipedia is subject to the laws (in particular, <a href="/wiki/Copyright" title="Copyright">copyright</a> laws) of the United States and of the U.S. state of <a href="/wiki/Virginia" title="Virginia">Virginia</a>, where the majority of Wikipedia's servers are located. Beyond legal matters, the editorial principles of Wikipedia are embodied in the <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Five_pillars" title="Wikipedia:Five pillars">"five pillars"</a> and in numerous <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:List_of_policies_and_guidelines" title="Wikipedia:List of policies and guidelines">policies and guidelines</a> intended to appropriately shape content. Even these rules are stored in wiki form, and Wikipedia editors write and revise the website's policies and guidelines.<sup id="cite_ref-pcworld_who.27s_behind_WP_91-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-pcworld_who.27s_behind_WP-91">[84]</a></sup> Editors can <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Enforcement" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:Enforcement">enforce these rules</a> by deleting or modifying non-compliant material. Originally, rules on the non-English editions of Wikipedia were based on a translation of the rules for the English Wikipedia. They have since diverged to some extent.<sup id="cite_ref-WP_some_sites_stable_versions_1_76-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WP_some_sites_stable_versions_1-76">[70]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Content_policies_and_guidelines">Content policies and guidelines<span id="Content_policies"></span></span></h3>
<p>According to the rules on the English Wikipedia, each entry in Wikipedia must be about a topic that is <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/encyclopedic" class="extiw" title="wikt:encyclopedic">encyclopedic</a> and is not a dictionary entry or dictionary-like.<sup id="cite_ref-WP_content_policy_1_92-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WP_content_policy_1-92">[85]</a></sup> A topic should also meet <a href="/wiki/Notability_in_the_English_Wikipedia" title="Notability in the English Wikipedia">Wikipedia's standards of "notability"</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-WP_notability_guide_1_93-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WP_notability_guide_1-93">[86]</a></sup> which generally means that the topic must have been covered in mainstream media or major academic journal sources that are independent of the article's subject. Further, Wikipedia intends to convey only knowledge that is already established and recognized.<sup id="cite_ref-NOR_94-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NOR-94">[87]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:No_original_research" title="Wikipedia:No original research">It must not present original research</a>. A claim that is likely to be challenged requires a reference to a <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Identifying_reliable_sources" title="Wikipedia:Identifying reliable sources">reliable source</a>. Among Wikipedia editors, this is often phrased as "verifiability, not truth" to express the idea that the readers, not the encyclopedia, are ultimately responsible for checking the truthfulness of the articles and making their own interpretations.<sup id="cite_ref-WP_Verifiability_policy_1_95-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WP_Verifiability_policy_1-95">[88]</a></sup> This can at times lead to the removal of information that is valid.<sup id="cite_ref-IHT_WP_valid_info_wrong_removable_1_96-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-IHT_WP_valid_info_wrong_removable_1-96">[89]</a></sup> Finally, Wikipedia must not take sides.<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated2_97-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated2-97">[90]</a></sup> All opinions and viewpoints, if attributable to external sources, must enjoy an appropriate share of coverage within an article.<sup id="cite_ref-alternet_WP_unethical_editing_destroy.27s_credibility_1_98-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-alternet_WP_unethical_editing_destroy.27s_credibility_1-98">[91]</a></sup> This is known as neutral point of view (NPOV).</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Governance">Governance</span></h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Further information: <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Administration" title="Wikipedia:Administration">Wikipedia:Administration</a></div>
<p>Wikipedia's initial <a href="/wiki/Anarchy" title="Anarchy">anarchy</a> integrated <a href="/wiki/Democracy" title="Democracy">democratic</a> and hierarchical elements over time.<sup id="cite_ref-99" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-99">[92]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-100" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-100">[93]</a></sup> An article is not considered to be owned by its creator or any other editor and is not vetted by any recognized authority.<sup id="cite_ref-101" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-101">[94]</a></sup> Wikipedia's contributors avoid a <a href="/wiki/Tragedy_of_the_commons" title="Tragedy of the commons">tragedy of the commons</a> by internalizing benefits. They do this by experiencing <a href="/wiki/Flow_(psychology)" title="Flow (psychology)">flow</a> and identifying with and gaining status in the Wikipedia community.<sup id="cite_ref-102" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-102">[95]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Administrators">Administrators</span></h3>
<p>Editors in good standing in the community can run for one of many levels of volunteer stewardship: this begins with "<a href="/wiki/Administrators_(Wikipedia)" class="mw-redirect" title="Administrators (Wikipedia)">administrator</a>",<sup id="cite_ref-103" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-103">[96]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-David_Mehegan_104-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-David_Mehegan-104">[97]</a></sup> privileged users who can delete pages, prevent articles from being changed in case of vandalism or editorial disputes, and try to prevent certain persons from editing. Despite the name, administrators are not supposed to enjoy any special privilege in decision-making; instead, their powers are mostly limited to making edits that have project-wide effects and thus are disallowed to ordinary editors, and to implement restrictions intended to prevent certain persons from making disruptive edits (such as vandalism).<sup id="cite_ref-105" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-105">[98]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-106" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-106">[99]</a></sup></p>
<p>Fewer editors become administrators than in years past, in part because the process of vetting potential Wikipedia administrators has become more rigorous.<sup id="cite_ref-107" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-107">[100]</a></sup></p>
<p><i>Bureaucrats</i> name new administrators, solely upon the recommendations from the community.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Dispute_resolution">Dispute resolution</span></h3>
<p>Wikipedians often have disputes regarding content, which may result in repeatedly making opposite changes to an article, known as <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:EW" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:EW">edit warring</a><sup id="cite_ref-108" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-108">[101]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-NBC_WP_editorial_warzone_1_109-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NBC_WP_editorial_warzone_1-109">[102]</a></sup> Over time, Wikipedia has developed a semi-formal dispute resolution process to assist in such circumstances. In order to determine community consensus, editors can raise issues at appropriate community forums,<sup id="cite_ref-110" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-110">[notes 8]</a></sup> or seek outside input through <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Third_opinion" title="Wikipedia:Third opinion">third opinion requests</a> or by initiating a more general community discussion known as a <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:RfC" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:RfC">request for comment</a>.</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Arbitration_Committee">Arbitration Committee</span></h4>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Arbitration_Committee" title="Arbitration Committee">Arbitration Committee</a></div>
<p>The Arbitration Committee presides over the ultimate dispute resolution process. Although disputes usually arise from a disagreement between two opposing views on how an article should read, the Arbitration Committee explicitly refuses to directly rule on the specific view that should be adopted. Statistical analyses suggest that the committee ignores the content of disputes and rather focuses on the way disputes are conducted,<sup id="cite_ref-emory_disputes_handled_1_111-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-emory_disputes_handled_1-111">[103]</a></sup> functioning not so much to resolve disputes and make peace between conflicting editors, but to weed out problematic editors while allowing potentially productive editors back in to participate. Therefore, the committee does not dictate the content of articles, although it sometimes condemns content changes when it deems the new content violates Wikipedia policies (for example, if the new content is considered <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Neutral_point_of_view" title="Wikipedia:Neutral point of view">biased</a>). Its remedies include cautions and <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Probation" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:Probation">probations</a> (used in 63% of cases) and <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:BAN" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:BAN">banning editors from articles</a> (43%), subject matters (23%) or Wikipedia (16%). Complete bans from Wikipedia are generally limited to instances of impersonation and <a href="/wiki/Anti-social_behavior" class="mw-redirect" title="Anti-social behavior">anti-social behavior</a>. When conduct is not impersonation or anti-social, but rather anti-consensus or in violation of editing policies, remedies tend to be limited to warnings.<sup id="cite_ref-112" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-112">[104]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Community">Community</span></h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia_community" title="Wikipedia community">Wikipedia community</a></div>

<p>Each article and each user of Wikipedia has an associated "Talk" page. These form the primary communication channel for editors to discuss, coordinate and debate.<sup id="cite_ref-113" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-113">[105]</a></sup></p>

Wikipedians and <a href="/wiki/British_Museum" title="British Museum">British Museum</a> curators collaborate on the article <a href="/wiki/Hoxne_Hoard" title="Hoxne Hoard">Hoxne Hoard</a> in June 2010</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Wikipedia's community has been described as <a href="/wiki/Cult" title="Cult">cult</a>-like,<sup id="cite_ref-114" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-114">[106]</a></sup> although not always with entirely negative connotations.<sup id="cite_ref-115" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-115">[107]</a></sup> The project's preference for cohesiveness, even if it requires compromise that includes disregard of <a href="/wiki/Credential" title="Credential">credentials</a>, has been referred to as "<a href="/wiki/Anti-elitism" class="mw-redirect" title="Anti-elitism">anti-elitism</a>".<sup id="cite_ref-116" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-116">[108]</a></sup></p>
<p>Wikipedians sometimes award one another <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Barnstars" title="Wikipedia:Barnstars">virtual barnstars</a> for good work. These personalized tokens of appreciation reveal a wide range of valued work extending far beyond simple editing to include social support, administrative actions, and types of articulation work.<sup id="cite_ref-117" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-117">[109]</a></sup></p>
<p>Wikipedia does not require that its editors and contributors provide identification.<sup id="cite_ref-user_identification_118-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-user_identification-118">[110]</a></sup> As Wikipedia grew, "Who writes Wikipedia?" became one of the questions frequently asked on the project.<sup id="cite_ref-119" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-119">[111]</a></sup> Jimmy Wales once argued that only "a community ... a dedicated group of a few hundred volunteers" makes the bulk of contributions to Wikipedia and that the project is therefore "much like any traditional organization".<sup id="cite_ref-blodget_120-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-blodget-120">[112]</a></sup> In 2008, a <i>Slate</i> magazine article reported that: "According to researchers in Palo Alto, 1 percent of Wikipedia users are responsible for about half of the site's edits."<sup id="cite_ref-121" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-121">[113]</a></sup> This method of evaluating contributions was later disputed by <a href="/wiki/Aaron_Swartz" title="Aaron Swartz">Aaron Swartz</a>, who noted that several articles he sampled had large portions of their content (measured by number of characters) contributed by users with low edit counts.<sup id="cite_ref-122" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-122">[114]</a></sup></p>
<p><span id="Decline_in_participation_since_2007"></span> The English Wikipedia has <a href="/wiki/Special:Statistics" title="Special:Statistics">5,430,154</a> articles, <a href="/wiki/Special:ActiveUsers" title="Special:ActiveUsers">31,228,278</a> registered editors, and <a href="/wiki/Special:ActiveUsers" title="Special:ActiveUsers">120,700</a> active editors. An editor is considered active if they have made one or more edits in the past thirty days.</p>
<p>Editors who fail to comply with Wikipedia cultural rituals, such as signing talk page comments, may implicitly signal that they are Wikipedia outsiders, increasing the odds that Wikipedia insiders may target or discount their contributions. Becoming a Wikipedia insider involves non-trivial costs: the contributor is expected to learn Wikipedia-specific technological codes, submit to a sometimes convoluted dispute resolution process, and learn a "baffling culture rich with in-jokes and insider references".<sup id="cite_ref-labor_squeeze_on_WP_1_123-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-labor_squeeze_on_WP_1-123">[115]</a></sup> Editors who do not log in are in some sense second-class citizens on Wikipedia,<sup id="cite_ref-labor_squeeze_on_WP_1_123-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-labor_squeeze_on_WP_1-123">[115]</a></sup> as "participants are accredited by members of the wiki community, who have a vested interest in preserving the quality of the work product, on the basis of their ongoing participation",<sup id="cite_ref-legal_edu_and_WP_1_124-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-legal_edu_and_WP_1-124">[116]</a></sup> but the contribution histories of anonymous unregistered editors recognized only by their <a href="/wiki/IP_addresses" class="mw-redirect" title="IP addresses">IP addresses</a> cannot be attributed to a particular editor with certainty.</p>
<p>A 2007 study by researchers from <a href="/wiki/Dartmouth_College" title="Dartmouth College">Dartmouth College</a> found that "anonymous and infrequent contributors to Wikipedia [...] are as reliable a source of knowledge as those contributors who register with the site".<sup id="cite_ref-sciam_good_samaritans_1_125-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sciam_good_samaritans_1-125">[117]</a></sup> Jimmy Wales stated in 2009 that "(I)t turns out over 50% of all the edits are done by just .7% of the users... 524 people... And in fact the most active 2%, which is 1400 people, have done 73.4% of all the edits."<sup id="cite_ref-blodget_120-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-blodget-120">[112]</a></sup> However, <i><a href="/wiki/Business_Insider" title="Business Insider">Business Insider</a></i> editor and journalist <a href="/wiki/Henry_Blodget" title="Henry Blodget">Henry Blodget</a> showed in 2009 that in a random sample of articles, most content in Wikipedia (measured by the amount of contributed text that survives to the latest sampled edit) is created by "outsiders", while most editing and formatting is done by "insiders".<sup id="cite_ref-blodget_120-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-blodget-120">[112]</a></sup></p>
<p>A 2008 study found that Wikipedians were less agreeable, open, and conscientious than others,<sup id="cite_ref-liebertonline_view_on_WP_users_1_126-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-liebertonline_view_on_WP_users_1-126">[118]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-newscientist_view_on_WP_users_1_127-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-newscientist_view_on_WP_users_1-127">[119]</a></sup> although a later commentary pointed out serious flaws, including that the data showed higher openness, that the differences with the control group were small as were the samples.<sup id="cite_ref-128" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-128">[120]</a></sup> According to a 2009 study, there is "evidence of growing resistance from the Wikipedia community to new content".<sup id="cite_ref-newscientist_WP_boom_to_bust_1_129-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-newscientist_WP_boom_to_bust_1-129">[121]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Diversity">Diversity</span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:WMF_Strategic_Plan_Survey.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/WMF_Strategic_Plan_Survey.svg/220px-WMF_Strategic_Plan_Survey.svg.png" width="220" height="181" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/WMF_Strategic_Plan_Survey.svg/330px-WMF_Strategic_Plan_Survey.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/WMF_Strategic_Plan_Survey.svg/440px-WMF_Strategic_Plan_Survey.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="535" data-file-height="440" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:WMF_Strategic_Plan_Survey.svg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Wikipedia editor demographics (2008)</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>One study found that the contributor base to Wikipedia "was barely 13% women; the average age of a contributor was in the mid-20s".<sup id="cite_ref-130" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-130">[122]</a></sup> A 2011 study by researchers from the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Minnesota" title="University of Minnesota">University of Minnesota</a> found that females comprised 16.1% of the 38,497 editors who started editing Wikipedia during 2009.<sup id="cite_ref-131" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-131">[123]</a></sup> In a January 2011 <i><a href="/wiki/New_York_Times" class="mw-redirect" title="New York Times">New York Times</a></i> article, Noam Cohen observed that just 13% of Wikipedia's contributors are female according to a 2008 Wikimedia Foundation survey.<sup id="cite_ref-132" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-132">[124]</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Sue_Gardner" title="Sue Gardner">Sue Gardner</a>, a former executive director of the Wikimedia Foundation, hoped to see female contributions increase to 25% by 2015.<sup id="cite_ref-NYT_WP_contributors_gender_1_133-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NYT_WP_contributors_gender_1-133">[125]</a></sup> Linda Basch, president of the National Council for Research on Women, noted the contrast in these Wikipedia editor statistics with the percentage of women currently completing bachelor's degrees, master's degrees and PhD programs in the United States (all at rates of 50 percent or greater).<sup id="cite_ref-NYT_WP_male_domination_1_134-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NYT_WP_male_domination_1-134">[126]</a></sup></p>
<p>In response, various universities have hosted <a href="/wiki/Edit-a-thon" title="Edit-a-thon">edit-a-thons</a> to encourage more women to participate in the Wikipedia community. In fall 2013, 15 colleges and universities — including Yale, Brown, and Pennsylvania State — offered college credit for students to "write feminist thinking" about technology into Wikipedia.<sup id="cite_ref-135" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-135">[127]</a></sup> Estimates of the diversity of contributors by educational level have indicated that sixty-two percent of Wikipedia's editors are at the high school and undergraduate college level of education.<sup id="cite_ref-136" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-136">[128]</a></sup></p>
<p>In August 2014, Wikipedia co-founder <a href="/wiki/Jimmy_Wales" title="Jimmy Wales">Jimmy Wales</a> said in a BBC interview that the <a href="/wiki/Wikimedia_Foundation" title="Wikimedia Foundation">Wikimedia Foundation</a> was "... really doubling down our efforts ..." to reach 25% of female editors (originally targeted by 2015), since the Foundation had "totally failed" so far. Wales said "a lot of things need to happen ... a lot of outreach, a lot of software changes".<sup id="cite_ref-BBC_137-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-BBC-137">[129]</a></sup> Andrew Lih, writing in <i>The New York Times</i>, was quoted by <a href="/wiki/Bloomberg_News" title="Bloomberg News">Bloomberg News</a> in December 2016 as supporting Wales comments concerning shortfalls in Wikipedia's outreach to female editors. Lih states his concern with the question indicating that: "How can you get people to participate in an (editing) environment that feels unsafe, where identifying yourself as a woman, as a feminist, could open you up to ugly, intimidating behavior".<sup id="cite_ref-138" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-138">[130]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Language_editions">Language editions</span></h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/List_of_Wikipedias" title="List of Wikipedias">List of Wikipedias</a></div>
<p>There are currently 295 language editions of Wikipedia (also called <i>language versions</i>, or simply <i>Wikipedias</i>). Thirteen of these have over one million articles each (<a href="/wiki/English_Wikipedia" title="English Wikipedia">English</a>, <a href="/wiki/Swedish_Wikipedia" title="Swedish Wikipedia">Swedish</a>, <a href="/wiki/Cebuano_Wikipedia" class="mw-redirect" title="Cebuano Wikipedia">Cebuano</a>, <a href="/wiki/German_Wikipedia" title="German Wikipedia">German</a>, <a href="/wiki/Dutch_Wikipedia" title="Dutch Wikipedia">Dutch</a>, <a href="/wiki/French_Wikipedia" title="French Wikipedia">French</a>, <a href="/wiki/Russian_Wikipedia" title="Russian Wikipedia">Russian</a>, <a href="/wiki/Italian_Wikipedia" title="Italian Wikipedia">Italian</a>, <a href="/wiki/Spanish_Wikipedia" title="Spanish Wikipedia">Spanish</a>, <a href="/wiki/Waray-Waray_Wikipedia" class="mw-redirect" title="Waray-Waray Wikipedia">Waray-Waray</a>, <a href="/wiki/Polish_Wikipedia" title="Polish Wikipedia">Polish</a>, <a href="/wiki/Vietnamese_Wikipedia" title="Vietnamese Wikipedia">Vietnamese</a> and <a href="/wiki/Japanese_Wikipedia" title="Japanese Wikipedia">Japanese</a>), five more have over 500,000 articles (<a href="/wiki/Portuguese_Wikipedia" title="Portuguese Wikipedia">Portuguese</a>, <a href="/wiki/Chinese_Wikipedia" title="Chinese Wikipedia">Chinese</a>, <a href="/wiki/Ukrainian_Wikipedia" title="Ukrainian Wikipedia">Ukrainian</a>, <a href="/wiki/Catalan_Wikipedia" title="Catalan Wikipedia">Catalan</a> and <a href="/wiki/Persian_Wikipedia" title="Persian Wikipedia">Persian</a>), 40 more have over 100,000 articles, and 77 more have over 10,000 articles.<sup id="cite_ref-ListOfWikipedias_139-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ListOfWikipedias-139">[131]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-WP_list_of_WPs_1_140-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WP_list_of_WPs_1-140">[132]</a></sup> The largest, the English Wikipedia, has over 5.4 million articles. As of January 2017<sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Wikipedia&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, according to Alexa, the English <a href="/wiki/Subdomain" title="Subdomain">subdomain</a> (en.wikipedia.org; English Wikipedia) receives approximately 55% of Wikipedia's cumulative traffic, with the remaining split among the other languages (Russian: 9%; Japanese: 7%; Spanish: 6%; French: 4%).<sup id="cite_ref-Alexa_siteinfo_10-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Alexa_siteinfo-10">[7]</a></sup> As of June 2017, the six largest language editions are (in order of article count) the <a href="/wiki/English_Wikipedia" title="English Wikipedia">English</a>, <a href="/wiki/Cebuano_Wikipedia" class="mw-redirect" title="Cebuano Wikipedia">Cebuano</a>, <a href="/wiki/Swedish_Wikipedia" title="Swedish Wikipedia">Swedish</a>, <a href="/wiki/German_Wikipedia" title="German Wikipedia">German</a>, <a href="/wiki/Dutch_Wikipedia" title="Dutch Wikipedia">Dutch</a>, and <a href="/wiki/French_Wikipedia" title="French Wikipedia">French</a> Wikipedias.<sup id="cite_ref-WP_list_of_WPs_by_article_1_141-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-WP_list_of_WPs_by_article_1-141">[133]</a></sup></p>
